China Vanke, Beiqi Foton, Construction Bank, Baoshan: China Equity Preview

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-04-05T16:00:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-05/china-vanke-construction-bank-baoshan-china-equity-preview.html
Bank and property developer shares
may have unusual moves in  China  trading after the People’s Bank
of China raised  interest rates  for the fourth time since the end
of the global financial crisis. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and prices are as of the previous close, unless stated
otherwise.  The Shanghai Composite Index added 39.3, or 1.3 percent, to
2,967.41 on April 1. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  advanced 1.5 percent to
3,272.73. Stock markets in China were closed on Monday and
Tuesday for the Tomb Sweeping festival.  China raised interest rates to restrain inflation and limit
the risk of asset bubbles in the fastest-growing major economy.
The benchmark one-year lending rate will increase to 6.31
percent from 6.06 percent, effective today, the People’s Bank of
China said yesterday. The one-year deposit rate will rise to
3.25 percent from 3 percent.  Property developers: China Vanke Co. (000002 CH), the
nation’s biggest listed property developer, rose 1.5 percent to
8.82 yuan. Poly Real Estate Group Co. (600048 CH), the second
largest, rose 5.1 percent to 14.11 yuan.  Banks: Industrial & Commercial  Bank of China Ltd. (3988)  (601398
CH): The world’s largest lender by market value rose 0.7 percent
to 4.50 yuan.  China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (601939 CH): The
nation’s second-biggest lender rose 0.8 percent to 5.01 yuan.
 Bank of China Ltd. (601988)  (601988 CH): The nation’s third-largest
lender by market value, rose 1.2 percent to 3.37 yuan.  Beiqi Foton Motor Co. (600166 CH): The Chinese vehicle
manufacturer will build a 1.2 billion-shilling ($14.3 million)
assembly plant in  Kenya  by 2012, Business Daily reported, citing
Calvin Guo, general manager of Foton East Africa. The plant will
produce 10,000 vehicles a year, including buses, pick-up trucks
and light commercial vehicles, the Nairobi-based newspaper said.
The shares gained 2.4 percent to 23.84 yuan.  Baoshan Iron & Steel Co. (600019 CH): The price of  iron ore 
will likely fall in the next few years as the global production
of steel is likely to lose the “growth momentum” experienced
in the last five years, said NMDC Ltd.,  Asia ’s third-largest
iron ore producer. Baoshan gained 1.1 percent to 7.15 yuan.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  